Moi through the mois✨ French lesson ♥️
(A play on words- meaning me through the months)
.
This reel means more to me then just some video I made. It was a reel that became my first viral reel. I was giving my all for 6 months on social media and freelance to see if could make it or if I had to go back to a corporate job. After this, I started realizing what my niche could be… eventually I started sharing mini French lessons and culture throughout this platform. I was able to share both my backgrounds ( French and American ) and it was nice for it to be appreciated. Especially when I always felt torn or stuck in between. As I started becoming more comfortable and learning about myself as I posted on this platform. I started to actually grow and build this beautiful little community. What a circle. Thank you for being a part of my journey. I appreciate you. 
.
.
.

POV: you just learned how to use gold leaf and now pretend to be a master antique frame gilder ✨✨✨✨ Merci for teaching me such a beautiful and timeless art Catherine! @chateau_marcellus 
.
Gold leaf is real gold that has been beaten into an extremely thin, almost weightless sheet. Production of gold leaf is believed to have begun in 2600 BCE in ancient Egypt, later spreading to Europe, Asia and other countries throughout the world. ✨
.
One of the owners of the @chateau_marcellus , @cathrine_roger gave me a mini first lesson on how to do the folding process. If you love art and history, they have been renovating and working on preserving the beautiful @chateau_marcellus ! The first castle on site of Chateau Marcellus was built in the 14th-century. The land and the castle belonged until 1581 to King of France Henri de Navarre of duché d’Albret. The medieval castle was a fortress that defended the plain of the Garonne, and of which nothing remains to this day. In 1581, Henri IV sold the castle to Aymeric de Gasq, adviser to the Parliament of Bordeaux. The Chateau was kept in the family until the beginning of the 18th-century…

The construction of a new castle was undertaken around 1585. At the beginning of the 18th century, the Château became the property of the De Martin du Tyrac family, later called Martin du Tyrac de Marcellus. The works leading to the current shape of the Chateau Marcellus were carried out between 1772 and 1778 under the direction of the architect Richard-François Bonfin.

Henri IV, the founder of the Bourbon dynasty and King of France was one of the ancient owners of the Chateau Marcellus. The land and the castle belonged to him until 1581.
His retrospective full-length sculpture as a child is still standing in the main staircase of the Marcellus. The original sculpture, made from silver by the famous sculptor François-Joseph Bosio, is displayed in the Louvre Museum.
.
.
.

Don’t become a prisoner of your own reality, set yourself free by creating a life worth living!! Romanticize your life, be the person that you want to be, change your life and make your dreams real. 

Bisous my friends!! As I travel around France to see family, I am learning so much more about myself. Time is passing, and I truly find myself more “ at home”. I’ve lived so much back and forth throughout my life and following everyone’s wants and dreams other than my own. Im ready to take charge of my life again and be in control of my own happiness. 

I type this as hopes that my little revelation can maybe help you too if you are feeling stuck or stagnant… I’ve been feeling it for a while now and I’ve decided I’m done being sad and doing nothing about it. I’m not moving full time back to France yet for work and love reasons but I know it’s what I want. The big concrete jungle just is not for me anymore. It’s filled with passion, motivation, creatives, and power but I’m ready for birds, forests, architecture, slow living, and family. 

Sending love and positivity to all of you beautiful souls. 

Bisous,
Léanne 
.
.

You don’t have to try as hard, it’s just a natural respect and understanding of one another…and that’s beautiful.

I used to be very embarrassed about my past life and not tell anyone truly where I came from. Recently, I’ve realized how proud of myself I am. On social media, because of the life that I have been privileged to have and where I share my work and dreams on… I’ve gotten comments like “who did she marry to live like that” or “trust fund baby” or “she comes from wealth”… So as a woman, my understanding is that I can’t create my own success. And why not?! Why erase all my hard work, why undervalue me, why? 

A little more about me: I came to the USA not speaking any English. My single mother came with 2 kids and 7 suitcases. I’ve lived between my grandparents homes until we moved to the trailer park in the middle of Pennsylvania…and lived there until I was 14. 

In the United States, people call you “trailer trash”… it’s absolutely terrible and incorrect!!! I had a beautiful upbringing. I had everything I ever needed. I would not have changed a thing. A trailer park was a beautiful community to be a part of. It also allowed me to appreciate life and opportunities to jump on. To understand people. To love everyone. 

These are just some of my thoughts. I hope it is not taken wrong. This is not for attention. It is truly because I’ve finally become proud of where I came from and I love to share… 
.
.
.
.
.

In a few decades from now, you would give anything to be right back in this moment. In a few decades from now, you would give anything to be this age again, this healthy again, this full of life again. In a few decades from now, you would give anything to have acted most wholeheartedly on what was yours to take. In a few decades from now, you would wish that you made the most of your talents, of your time. You would wish that you had made more what was already yours. 🥀

When you reflect back on this period, you will only regret what you did not do. You will only regret that you were so fearful of making a mistake, you never made a move. You will only regret than in an effort to be accepted, you lost your voice, your spark, your truth. You will only regret that you had allowed the things you had to slip through your fingers, because you thought you were not enough for them. You thought you were unworthy of your own life, as though that is ever something a person could be.

You will regret how much time vou spent weeding at the surface and not pulling the hurt from the root. That you did not do what you knew you were meant to do, when you were meant to do it. That vou stayed when you knew you should go, that you kept delaying and lingering and placing all of your dreams into a someday that would never come.

In a few decades from now, what you will know for sure is that the life you wanted was one in which you made the most of what you already had. That the pieces were already on the table, that the door was already in the room.
You will realize that we are only ever meant to make the most of what is handed to us, both the goodness and the hurt. To pull out from inside of them gratitude, and awe; or wisdom, and learning. That life does not happen to us, but transpires through us.

All along, the only thing you were waiting on was yourself. ♥️

They called her « Lili de Montmartre »… She moved to Paris in the 20’s and over-romanticized the cobble stone streets glistening from the warm-lit lamp post by the stairs. She loved hearing hearing live jazz playing from outside busy restaurants at night and adored dreaming of the life she was already living. 🥀
.

I made this reel inspired by « Kiki de Montparnasse » She was a French model, chanteuse, actress, memoirist and painter during the Jazz Age. She flourished in, and helped define, the liberated culture of Paris in the so-called Années folles (« crazy years » in French). She became one of the most famous models of the 20th century and in the history of avant-garde art.
